1
00:00:32,831 --> 00:00:36,844
It's like this. A dead plaintiff
is rarely worth as much

2
00:00:36,885 --> 00:00:39,338
as a living,
severely maimed plaintiff.

3
00:00:39,580 --> 00:00:42,249
However, if it's a long,
agonising death,

4
00:00:42,291 --> 00:00:44,960
as opposed to a quick drowning
or car wreck,

5
00:00:45,002 --> 00:00:47,304
the value can rise considerably.

6
00:00:47,446 --> 00:00:51,725
A dead adult in his 20s is worth less
than a middle-aged one,

7
00:00:51,967 --> 00:00:54,194
a dead woman less than a dead man,

8
00:00:54,236 --> 00:00:57,022
single adults less than married,

9
00:00:57,064 --> 00:01:00,409
black less than white,
poor less than rich.

10
00:01:01,051 --> 00:01:03,796
But the perfect victim
is a white, male, professional -

11
00:01:04,138 --> 00:01:06,224
40 years old, at the height
of his earning power,

12
00:01:06,366 --> 00:01:09,494
struck down in his prime.

13
00:01:10,335 --> 00:01:12,580
And the most imperfect?

14
00:01:12,721 --> 00:01:15,450
Well, in the calculus
of personal injury law,

15
00:01:15,491 --> 00:01:18,761
a dead child is worth least of all.

16
00:01:22,798 --> 00:01:24,424
A million dollars he turns down.

17
00:01:24,466 --> 00:01:28,178
- One million dollars!
- I don't believe their story.

18
00:01:28,220 --> 00:01:30,556
- It's true.
- Come on!

19
00:01:30,597 --> 00:01:33,100
- Hey, Eddie. How you doing?
- Good.

20
00:01:33,141 --> 00:01:35,602
Do me a favour - shut the fuck up.

21
00:01:35,644 --> 00:01:39,731
Our banker there doesn't know
Jan refused a million.

22
00:01:39,773 --> 00:01:41,942
- Sorry.
- Yeah.

23
00:01:45,112 --> 00:01:46,989
Asshole.

24
00:02:09,469 --> 00:02:12,389
How's your head? Up?

25
00:02:16,143 --> 00:02:20,063
How's that? OK?
Are you comfortable?

26
00:02:21,398 --> 00:02:23,692
Open?

27
00:02:31,950 --> 00:02:34,244
Here we go.

28
00:02:43,128 --> 00:02:45,214
All rise.

29
00:02:47,049 --> 00:02:49,176
This court is now in session.

30
00:02:49,259 --> 00:02:53,096
The Honourable
Constance Mullen presiding.

31
00:02:53,138 --> 00:02:55,182
Would you like some water?

32
00:02:55,641 --> 00:02:58,393
Carney versus Massachusetts
General Hospital -

33
00:02:58,477 --> 00:03:01,188
case number 812725.

34
00:03:03,815 --> 00:03:06,610
Attorneys,
please state your appearance.

35
00:03:06,693 --> 00:03:08,570
Randolph Woodside, Mass General.

36
00:03:09,655 --> 00:03:11,865
Greg Monk,
Massachusetts General Hospital.

37
00:03:12,783 --> 00:03:14,409
Harold Peshniak, Mass General.

38
00:03:15,494 --> 00:03:17,246
Jan Schlichtmann for Paul Carney.

39
00:03:17,329 --> 00:03:20,916
Kevin Conway for Mr Carney,
Your Honour.

40
00:03:20,958 --> 00:03:24,253
Mr Schlichtmann, we're ready
for your opening statement.

41
00:03:48,235 --> 00:03:51,321
Your Honour,
if it please the court,

42
00:03:51,405 --> 00:03:54,408
the parties involved
have agreed to a settlement.

43
00:05:05,437 --> 00:05:08,190
Personal injury law
has a bad reputation.

44
00:05:08,273 --> 00:05:11,026
They call us ambulance chasers,
bottom feeders,

45
00:05:11,109 --> 00:05:14,071
vultures preying on
the misfortunes of others.

46
00:05:14,112 --> 00:05:18,367
If that's true, why do I lie awake
worrying about my clients?

47
00:05:18,450 --> 00:05:21,286
Why is their pain my pain?

48
00:05:21,370 --> 00:05:26,500
I wish I didn't empathise.
It'd be a lot easier.

49
00:05:47,938 --> 00:05:50,816
We're speaking to Jan Schlichtmann,
personal injury attorney

50
00:05:50,899 --> 00:05:53,944
and according to Boston magazine -
have you seen this? -

51
00:05:54,027 --> 00:05:57,281
one of Boston's
ten most eligible bachelors.

52
00:06:10,711 --> 00:06:13,338
Let's go back to the phones. Woburn,
you're on the air.

53
00:06:16,049 --> 00:06:17,551
Mr Schlichtmann,
it's Anne Anderson.

54
00:06:17,634 --> 00:06:19,636
- Hello.
- How are you?

55
00:06:19,720 --> 00:06:22,264
Very well. You? Sounds pretty.

56
00:06:23,348 --> 00:06:25,392
How come you never call me?

57
00:06:25,475 --> 00:06:29,104
- If I had your number, I would.
- You have it.

58
00:06:29,187 --> 00:06:32,941
- I do?
- You have no idea who I am?

59
00:06:33,066 --> 00:06:35,611
- Is this Ricky?
- No.

60
00:06:35,694 --> 00:06:38,989
You see, my son died of leukaemia
two years ago.

61
00:06:39,072 --> 00:06:42,200
- Your firm is handling the case.
- We are?

62
00:06:42,284 --> 00:06:45,120
The reason I'm calling you here

63
00:06:45,203 --> 00:06:50,250
is because my calls to your offices
have gone unreturned for weeks.

64
00:06:50,334 --> 00:06:52,628
- Sorry, your name was?
- Anne.

65
00:06:52,753 --> 00:06:54,880
- Anne...
- Anderson.

66
00:06:54,922 --> 00:06:59,426
I'm writing that down.
I'm gonna take care of this.

67
00:07:01,803 --> 00:07:03,597
Why don't you come up to Woburn

68
00:07:03,680 --> 00:07:08,393
and actually meet a few of those
people whose pain is your pain?

69
00:07:11,647 --> 00:07:13,357
Let me picture this.

70
00:07:13,440 --> 00:07:17,444
She called you, she cried.
You felt sorry and you cried.

71
00:07:17,527 --> 00:07:20,864
- Now she's mad.
- It's a good case.

72
00:07:20,948 --> 00:07:24,326
- She's not crying now!
- An orphan, but good.

73
00:07:24,409 --> 00:07:28,247
12 deaths over 15 years from
leukaemia - eight of them children.

74
00:07:28,372 --> 00:07:31,959
- That's unusual?
- Statistically. It's a small town.

75
00:07:32,042 --> 00:07:33,502
She lost a child?

76
00:07:34,628 --> 00:07:38,090
They think it's something to do
with the city's drinking water

77
00:07:38,173 --> 00:07:40,050
which they say tastes funny.

78
00:07:40,133 --> 00:07:42,219
What was she like before?

79
00:07:42,261 --> 00:07:46,014
- Do want to hear what it's about?
- No, I don't!

80
00:07:46,056 --> 00:07:48,559
I'd like to hear about it.

81
00:07:50,811 --> 00:07:53,146
Thank you, Kathy.

82
00:07:53,188 --> 00:07:55,899
There's a report here
from state inspectors

83
00:07:55,983 --> 00:07:59,027
saying that the water
from two city wells

84
00:07:59,111 --> 00:08:02,531
is contaminated - or was
before they shut them down -

85
00:08:02,656 --> 00:08:05,951
with something called...
I can't pronounce this...

86
00:08:06,034 --> 00:08:08,161
trichlorethylene...ethylene,

87
00:08:08,245 --> 00:08:10,789
which the EPA lists
as a probable carcinogen.

88
00:08:10,914 --> 00:08:12,749
- Stop.
- There's more.

89
00:08:12,833 --> 00:08:18,046
No, from a financial standpoint,
this is not a sound investment.

90
00:08:18,171 --> 00:08:20,465
Probable is a euphemism
for unproven.

91
00:08:20,591 --> 00:08:24,011
To prove something like this,
you need new medical research.

92
00:08:24,094 --> 00:08:26,471
Is that our business -
medical research?

93
00:08:26,555 --> 00:08:31,018
And...and ask yourself,
why is this an orphan?

94
00:08:31,101 --> 00:08:34,521
It's been kicked around
before ending up on your desk.

95
00:08:34,605 --> 00:08:37,316
Gordon's right.

96
00:08:37,357 --> 00:08:41,153
I can appreciate
the theatrical value of dead kids.

97
00:08:41,194 --> 00:08:45,991
That's good. But that's all it has
going for it, and it's not enough.

98
00:08:47,117 --> 00:08:49,161
I'll get rid of it.

99
00:08:50,495 --> 00:08:53,832
I'll...just go up there and...

100
00:08:53,916 --> 00:08:58,253
You'll both start to cry again,
she'll be mad at me.

101
00:08:58,337 --> 00:09:02,507
I'll do it. I'll get rid of it.
Give it to me.

102
00:09:05,552 --> 00:09:07,221
Thank you.

103
00:09:17,189 --> 00:09:19,233
- There you go, sir.
- Thank you.

104
00:09:19,316 --> 00:09:21,193
- Drive careful.
- Yeah.

105
00:09:29,785 --> 00:09:31,828
When I stand on my porch,

106
00:09:31,912 --> 00:09:33,956
I can see the houses
where children died.

107
00:09:35,624 --> 00:09:39,753
These are the Kanes,
the Toomeys, the Zohners,

108
00:09:39,836 --> 00:09:43,590
the Robbins and the Aufieros.

109
00:09:43,715 --> 00:09:46,260
Now, I want to be clear.

110
00:09:46,385 --> 00:09:49,429
I'm not interested in money -
none of us are.

111
00:09:49,513 --> 00:09:54,560
What we want is to know what
happened. And we want an apology.

112
00:09:54,643 --> 00:09:57,312
- From who?
- Whoever did this.

113
00:09:57,396 --> 00:10:01,233
I want somebody to come and say,
"We're responsible.

114
00:10:01,358 --> 00:10:04,444
"We didn't mean it,
but we're sorry."

115
00:10:04,528 --> 00:10:06,572
But who is that?

116
00:10:08,574 --> 00:10:10,951
Well, we don't know.

117
00:10:11,034 --> 00:10:14,955
Mrs Anderson, our firm is
very small, just three attorneys.

118
00:10:15,038 --> 00:10:18,458
We can only take
so many cases at once

119
00:10:18,542 --> 00:10:22,963
and we have to be choosy because,
frankly, we can't afford to lose.

120
00:10:23,046 --> 00:10:28,093
We pay everything. We only get paid
if we win or settle.

121
00:10:28,176 --> 00:10:31,054
- I know.
- You want an apology.

122
00:10:31,138 --> 00:10:35,225
And I'd love to get you
that apology, but from who?

123
00:10:35,309 --> 00:10:39,146
Who is going to apologise to you and
pay me?

124
00:10:39,229 --> 00:10:42,608
There has to be a defendant
with very deep pockets.

125
00:10:42,691 --> 00:10:45,903
This is not
an inexpensive case to try.

126
00:10:49,197 --> 00:10:51,575
There's an old tannery out there.

127
00:10:51,658 --> 00:10:53,535
A tannery?

128
00:10:53,619 --> 00:10:56,163
And some other small factories.

129
00:11:01,710 --> 00:11:05,631
I really wish I could help you
but I can't. I'm sorry.

130
00:11:05,714 --> 00:11:11,428
Maybe you could go out to
the river, to the wells, and look.

131
00:11:11,511 --> 00:11:15,265
For what?
What would that accomplish?

132
00:11:19,603 --> 00:11:23,732
I do hope you find someone.
And I am sorry.

133
00:11:36,912 --> 00:11:40,415
- Thank you very much.
- Drive carefully.

134
00:14:42,764 --> 00:14:45,017
It was fate.

135
00:14:45,100 --> 00:14:50,063
I was meant to get that ticket,
at that moment, at that exact spot.

136
00:14:51,148 --> 00:14:53,275
Do you know who Beatrice is?

137
00:14:56,695 --> 00:14:58,864
Peter Pan peanut butter,

138
00:14:58,947 --> 00:15:00,282
Tropicana orange juice,

139
00:15:00,365 --> 00:15:01,909
Rosarita Mexican Food,

140
00:15:02,075 --> 00:15:05,996
Swiss Miss cocoa, Samsonite
luggage... The list goes on!

141
00:15:06,121 --> 00:15:08,457
- And the other one?
- W.R. Grace.

142
00:15:08,498 --> 00:15:10,626
Chemical plants in two dozen states,

143
00:15:10,667 --> 00:15:12,753
South America, Europe and Japan.

144
00:15:12,836 --> 00:15:14,963
- What's this?
- The ticket.

145
00:15:15,088 --> 00:15:17,925
No, I've got that right here.

146
00:15:18,008 --> 00:15:22,221
- I got two speeding tickets.
- A two-ticket town?

147
00:15:22,304 --> 00:15:24,765
Exactly.
Don't take your Caddie there.

148
00:15:24,890 --> 00:15:28,977
Kevin, it's a gold mine.
You almost let it get away.

149
00:15:29,019 --> 00:15:31,730
I almost let it get away.

150
00:15:36,068 --> 00:15:39,571
Lawsuits are war -
it's as simple as that.

151
00:15:39,655 --> 00:15:43,742
And they begin the same way,
with a declaration of war -

152
00:15:43,825 --> 00:15:45,869
the complaint.

153
00:15:45,953 --> 00:15:48,789
When you're a small firm
and they're big,

154
00:15:48,872 --> 00:15:50,999
steeped in history and wealth,

155
00:15:51,124 --> 00:15:53,502
with Persian carpets on the floor

156
00:15:53,585 --> 00:15:55,754
and Harvard diplomas on the walls,

157
00:15:55,837 --> 00:15:58,215
it's easy to be intimidated.

158
00:15:58,340 --> 00:16:00,676
Don't - that's what they want.

159
00:16:00,759 --> 00:16:03,595
That's what they expect,
like all bullies.

160
00:16:03,679 --> 00:16:05,973
That's how they win.

161
00:16:07,224 --> 00:16:09,685
I don't run away from bullies.

162
00:16:35,919 --> 00:16:37,671
Mr Facher...

163
00:16:37,754 --> 00:16:41,216
Mr Doyle asked
me to bring this to you.

164
00:16:51,643 --> 00:16:53,937
When?

165
00:16:53,979 --> 00:16:56,648
- When did he ask me?
- Yeah.

166
00:16:56,732 --> 00:16:57,900
Just now.

167
00:16:58,025 --> 00:17:02,779
On your lunch break?
That hardly seems fair.

168
00:17:02,863 --> 00:17:07,451
I almost never go to lunch, sir.
Too much to do.

169
00:17:07,492 --> 00:17:09,494
I just grab something.

170
00:17:09,578 --> 00:17:13,415
You know, I'd make a point
of taking an hour or so

171
00:17:13,540 --> 00:17:16,084
away from all the noise
and insanity.

172
00:17:16,210 --> 00:17:17,669
I should do that.

173
00:17:17,753 --> 00:17:21,173
I'd find a place that was
relatively quiet and peaceful,

174
00:17:21,256 --> 00:17:23,884
have a sandwich, read a magazine.

175
00:17:23,967 --> 00:17:27,471
Maybe listen to a game
if one was on.

176
00:17:29,223 --> 00:17:34,519
I'd make sure everyone knew not
to disturb me during that hour.

177
00:17:34,603 --> 00:17:38,190
Because that would be my time -
my own private time,

178
00:17:38,273 --> 00:17:42,110
which no-one, if they had any sense
of self-preservation,

179
00:17:42,194 --> 00:17:44,238
would dare interrupt.

180
00:17:45,989 --> 00:17:48,075
If I were you.

181
00:17:50,369 --> 00:17:51,453
I'm sorry.

182
00:18:11,014 --> 00:18:13,141
Jesus.

183
00:18:16,812 --> 00:18:18,730
Jesus!

184
00:18:26,154 --> 00:18:28,907
Jesus...

185
00:18:31,451 --> 00:18:35,289
Mr Facher, it's Bill Cheeseman -
Foley, Hoag and Elliot.

186
00:18:35,372 --> 00:18:37,082
We represent New York Grace.

187
00:18:37,165 --> 00:18:39,167
How you doing?

188
00:18:39,251 --> 00:18:43,088
Well, all right, I guess,
under the circumstances.

189
00:18:43,171 --> 00:18:44,965
What circumstances are those?

190
00:18:45,048 --> 00:18:47,885
Woburn - these outrageous charges.

191
00:18:47,968 --> 00:18:51,388
This bloodsucking
ambulance chaser, Schlichtmann.

192
00:18:51,471 --> 00:18:53,015
Who?

193
00:18:53,098 --> 00:18:57,227
We're co-defendants in a lawsuit,
Mr Facher, a very serious lawsuit.

194
00:18:57,311 --> 00:19:01,231
- What?
- What is that thumping?

195
00:19:03,734 --> 00:19:07,571
Yeah, well, it's gone now.
It was driving me crazy!

196
00:19:07,696 --> 00:19:11,366
I was wondering
if I could talk to you.

197
00:19:11,491 --> 00:19:15,954
- Could we meet for a drink or...
- What's on your mind?

198
00:19:16,038 --> 00:19:18,707
I'll tell you what I'm thinking.

199
00:19:18,790 --> 00:19:22,377
- Are you familiar with Rule 11?
- With what?

200
00:19:22,461 --> 00:19:24,755
Rule 11, a civil provision

201
00:19:24,838 --> 00:19:27,883
to prevent frivolous and
irresponsible lawsuits like this,

202
00:19:27,966 --> 00:19:31,011
and sanction quite severely
those who file them.

203
00:19:32,221 --> 00:19:36,350
Mr...Cheeseman. Cheeseman, is it?

204
00:19:38,936 --> 00:19:41,146
Mr Cheeseman. What is a fine?

205
00:19:41,271 --> 00:19:44,775
You get fined,
you pay it and carry on.

206
00:19:44,858 --> 00:19:50,239
If you're gonna knock a guy down,
do it so he can't get up again.

207
00:19:53,533 --> 00:19:56,286
What are you looking for
with this suit?

208
00:19:56,370 --> 00:19:59,039
Obviously, we're seeking
compensation for the families

209
00:19:59,122 --> 00:20:02,626
and punitive damages for wilful
negligence by these companies.

210
00:20:02,751 --> 00:20:05,837
But is that what
this is about - money?

211
00:20:05,921 --> 00:20:08,966
- No.
- Is that what matters most?

212
00:20:09,049 --> 00:20:11,843
- No.
- It's about this.

213
00:20:15,305 --> 00:20:17,140
And this.

214
00:20:20,602 --> 00:20:22,521
And this.

215
00:20:24,022 --> 00:20:25,691
Yeah.

216
00:20:27,067 --> 00:20:30,279
Yeah, I know, we have
no feelings, no compassion,

217
00:20:30,362 --> 00:20:32,364
no empathy for
our clients' suffering.

218
00:20:32,447 --> 00:20:34,199
Can I say something?

219
00:20:34,283 --> 00:20:37,119
What does that
have to do with anything?

220
00:20:37,202 --> 00:20:39,872
The lawyer who shares
his client's pain

221
00:20:39,955 --> 00:20:42,249
does his client
such a grave disservice

222
00:20:42,374 --> 00:20:45,794
he should have his licence
to practise taken away.

223
00:20:45,919 --> 00:20:49,381
It clouds his judgement,
and that's as useful

224
00:20:49,464 --> 00:20:52,634
as a doctor
who's frightened of blood.

225
00:20:52,718 --> 00:20:53,719
All rise.

226
00:20:55,387 --> 00:20:57,472
This court is now in session.

227
00:20:57,556 --> 00:21:00,767
The Honourable
Walter J Skinner presiding.

228
00:21:00,851 --> 00:21:02,895
Is this the only case?

229
00:21:02,978 --> 00:21:05,772
This is a lot of lawyers.

230
00:21:05,856 --> 00:21:07,691
Sit down.

231
00:21:12,571 --> 00:21:16,617
You're looking well.
The Red Sox must be in first place.

232
00:21:16,700 --> 00:21:19,786
Roger Clemens
is the answer to my prayers.

233
00:21:21,163 --> 00:21:23,165
You have some interest in this case?

234
00:21:23,248 --> 00:21:28,295
I'm a co-defendant, but it's not
my motion. It's Foley-Hoag's.

235
00:21:28,420 --> 00:21:30,714
- And that motion?
- Your Honour.

236
00:21:30,797 --> 00:21:33,759
- I'm Jan Schlichtmann.
- I know. Sit down.

237
00:21:35,677 --> 00:21:38,138
The matter before us seems simple.

238
00:21:38,222 --> 00:21:41,892
- Your Honour, it isn't.
- May I hear it?

239
00:21:42,017 --> 00:21:44,978
The intention here is to place me

240
00:21:45,020 --> 00:21:47,981
under a cloud of impropriety.

241
00:21:48,065 --> 00:21:50,359
- Really?
- Yes. What they're saying

242
00:21:50,484 --> 00:21:54,905
is that they know law and I don't,
they're real lawyers and I'm not.

243
00:21:54,988 --> 00:21:57,199
They're just trying to humiliate me.

244
00:21:57,282 --> 00:22:02,788
You are a personal injury lawyer,
aren't you? I think you'll survive.

245
00:22:03,705 --> 00:22:07,292
- See? It's starting already.
- No, you've started already.

246
00:22:07,417 --> 00:22:09,711
I'm on the defensive,
they're the defendants.

247
00:22:09,836 --> 00:22:13,465
Do you think
I might hear this motion

248
00:22:13,549 --> 00:22:17,052
before You explain to ME
what it's really about?

249
00:22:18,428 --> 00:22:20,889
- Of course.
- Thank you.

250
00:22:22,599 --> 00:22:28,021
Now, Mr...Cheeseman, is it?

251
00:22:31,817 --> 00:22:34,152
Your motion to dismiss
is based on?

252
00:22:34,236 --> 00:22:36,071
Rule 11, Your Honour.

253
00:22:36,154 --> 00:22:40,492
Specifically that Mr Schlichtmann had
no evidential grounds

254
00:22:40,534 --> 00:22:42,703
on which to bring this suit -

255
00:22:42,786 --> 00:22:47,583
only his knowledge that W.R. Grace
Corporation has a lot of money.

256
00:22:47,708 --> 00:22:49,126
Not true.

257
00:22:49,209 --> 00:22:53,422
He performed no real investigation,
did no research of any consequence,

258
00:22:53,505 --> 00:22:56,800
except perhaps
to review profit statements.

259
00:22:56,884 --> 00:23:01,471
And he's prepared his complaint
so inexpertly as to render it moot.

260
00:23:01,555 --> 00:23:05,601
- All untrue.
- Do you know what Rule 11 is?

261
00:23:05,684 --> 00:23:09,438
To be honest, Your Honour,
I had to look it up.

262
00:23:09,521 --> 00:23:15,277
I'll be honest, so did l.
Do you know why, Mr Cheeseman?

263
00:23:15,360 --> 00:23:18,155
Because it is so old and ambiguous

264
00:23:18,238 --> 00:23:21,617
few lawyers
waste their time with it, or mine.

265
00:23:21,700 --> 00:23:26,246
It's a non-issue, Mr Cheeseman.
Your motion is denied. Thank you.

266
00:23:26,330 --> 00:23:28,165
Thank you.

267
00:23:28,248 --> 00:23:30,792
- Anything else?
- No, Your Honour.

268
00:23:30,876 --> 00:23:32,794
Set a trial date.

269
00:23:32,878 --> 00:23:36,632
Excuse me, Mr Facher.
I'd like to thank you.

270
00:23:36,757 --> 00:23:41,178
That was very statesman-like of you
not to join that ridiculous attack.

271
00:23:43,472 --> 00:23:45,390
You're welcome.

272
00:23:48,644 --> 00:23:50,854
We have to show how

273
00:23:50,938 --> 00:23:54,524
the toxic solvents these factories
dumped on the land there,

274
00:23:54,608 --> 00:23:59,571
were drawn into the city wells here
and Well H over there,

275
00:23:59,696 --> 00:24:02,407
and then pumped
into east Woburn homes.

276
00:24:02,491 --> 00:24:05,994
So I'll need to inspect
and map the debris,

277
00:24:06,078 --> 00:24:08,372
drill some monitoring wells,

278
00:24:08,413 --> 00:24:12,125
conduct seismic tests, and so on.

279
00:24:12,167 --> 00:24:16,213
And you're talking about you
and a couple of assistants?

280
00:24:16,296 --> 00:24:19,675
No. I mean a team of
geologists and engineers.

281
00:24:19,758 --> 00:24:23,053
- A team?
- A big team.

282
00:24:26,515 --> 00:24:28,517
It's actually quite exciting.

283
00:24:28,600 --> 00:24:32,354
The nature of the contour
here means there's an effect -

284
00:24:32,437 --> 00:24:34,106
named after me, actually...

285
00:24:37,818 --> 00:24:43,031
In the shop, Mr Roberts,
you used solvents to clean brushes?

286
00:24:44,700 --> 00:24:49,705
What would you've done with that
stuff back in the 1970s and '80s?

287
00:24:49,788 --> 00:24:54,835
- Used solvent? Put it in drums.
- 35-gallon drums?

288
00:24:54,877 --> 00:24:57,462
What would you do with full drums?

289
00:24:57,546 --> 00:25:00,215
- Don't know.
- They just went?

290
00:25:00,299 --> 00:25:03,468
- Never noticed.
- Did you dump them?

291
00:25:03,552 --> 00:25:06,972
- No.
- Nothing like that?

292
00:25:07,014 --> 00:25:10,434
- Never noticed anyone who did?
- No.

293
00:25:10,517 --> 00:25:13,520
Just disappeared...

294
00:25:13,562 --> 00:25:16,231
What were your duties
at Grace, Mr Shalline?

295
00:25:16,315 --> 00:25:22,195
Discharge to the drains. Be sure
we weren't polluting the air.

296
00:25:22,279 --> 00:25:27,784
Then you know that chemicals
were deposited behind the plant?

297
00:25:27,868 --> 00:25:29,912
I don't know that.

298
00:25:29,995 --> 00:25:32,372
Six barrels of toxic waste

299
00:25:32,456 --> 00:25:36,710
were found there in a pit
and exhumed by city inspectors.

300
00:25:36,793 --> 00:25:38,795
- You didn't know?
- Nope.

301
00:25:38,879 --> 00:25:43,926
Back in 1965 did you
clean metal parts with solvent?

302
00:25:43,967 --> 00:25:45,093
Yes.

303
00:25:45,177 --> 00:25:47,888
- What kind?
- That I couldn't say.

304
00:25:47,971 --> 00:25:52,726
Did you ever notice
the name trichlorethylene or TCE?

305
00:25:52,809 --> 00:25:54,061
I don't know.

306
00:25:54,144 --> 00:25:58,523
But you'd put it in barrels
when you were finished, right?

307
00:25:58,607 --> 00:25:59,608
Yes.

308
00:25:59,733 --> 00:26:04,279
Did you ever see
what happened to these barrels?

309
00:26:04,321 --> 00:26:05,280
Yes.

310
00:26:15,541 --> 00:26:16,959
What was that?

311
00:26:20,254 --> 00:26:23,924
- They get dumped.
- Where?

312
00:26:24,049 --> 00:26:27,553
- Out back, in the ground.
- You saw this?

313
00:26:27,678 --> 00:26:29,137
Yes.

314
00:26:29,221 --> 00:26:31,098
- When?
- My coffee break.

315
00:26:31,181 --> 00:26:35,936
I would go out and hit
nine-iron shots with golf balls.

316
00:26:36,019 --> 00:26:38,063
Do you want a break?

317
00:26:38,146 --> 00:26:41,817
- Do you need a break?
- No.

318
00:26:41,942 --> 00:26:46,822
Did you see who was dumping
the stuff while hitting golf balls?

319
00:26:47,906 --> 00:26:52,452
- What do you mean?
- The names of people.

320
00:26:55,622 --> 00:26:57,583
He wants to tell us.

321
00:26:57,666 --> 00:27:01,336
He won't tell us.
He has to work there.

322
00:27:01,461 --> 00:27:07,050
But he lives near Anne Anderson.
He sees her every day.

323
00:27:34,870 --> 00:27:39,291
- Mr Love, do you have any children?
- Yes, I do.

324
00:27:39,374 --> 00:27:41,376
- Eight of them.
- Eight?

325
00:27:41,460 --> 00:27:44,671
My goodness! That's quite a family.

326
00:27:45,881 --> 00:27:49,718
What do you think
of the water in Woburn?

327
00:27:49,760 --> 00:27:52,095
Now? It's all right.

328
00:27:52,221 --> 00:27:54,681
What about then, 15 years ago?

329
00:27:54,806 --> 00:27:58,894
It had an odour then.
Chlorine or something.

330
00:28:00,187 --> 00:28:03,065
- Did you drink it?
- Yeah.

331
00:28:03,148 --> 00:28:06,735
- The kids?
- Yes.

332
00:28:08,987 --> 00:28:12,407
Were you concerned when you found
the wells were contaminated?

333
00:28:12,532 --> 00:28:16,370
I object to that.
You don't have to answer that.

334
00:28:18,872 --> 00:28:22,626
- Yeah, I was concerned.
- For your family?

335
00:28:22,709 --> 00:28:23,710
Yes.

336
00:28:23,794 --> 00:28:27,881
Has any member of your family
had any unusual illness?

337
00:28:27,965 --> 00:28:33,178
You don't have to answer
any of these type of questions.

338
00:28:33,220 --> 00:28:35,180
- Yeah.
- What kind?

339
00:28:35,264 --> 00:28:37,266
One of my sons has seizures,

340
00:28:37,349 --> 00:28:40,310
my eldest daughter
has had two miscarriages

341
00:28:40,394 --> 00:28:42,437
and my youngest was born with...

342
00:28:42,521 --> 00:28:46,024
Are we going to go through
their entire medical history?

343
00:28:46,108 --> 00:28:48,652
If you don't want to hear, leave.

344
00:28:48,735 --> 00:28:52,072
What's wrong? We're deposing
Grace employees, not Beatrice.

345
00:28:52,155 --> 00:28:57,744
- I have a right to be here.
- Then sit down and shut up!

346
00:29:07,671 --> 00:29:09,506
Mr Love,

347
00:29:09,590 --> 00:29:15,345
are you aware that some of your
neighbours have had leukaemia?

348
00:29:15,429 --> 00:29:17,139
Yes, I am.

349
00:29:18,515 --> 00:29:20,559
They think it's the water.

350
00:29:21,643 --> 00:29:25,689
Al, that water
hasn't made anybody sick.

351
00:29:27,733 --> 00:29:32,529
- How do you know?
- I just do.

352
00:29:33,739 --> 00:29:36,825
A lot of people in my neighbourhood
are dead,

353
00:29:36,909 --> 00:29:39,453
or dying, Mr Chessman,
from something.

354
00:29:41,622 --> 00:29:44,917
Look, if I took a hundred pennies

355
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:47,336
and threw them in the air,

356
00:29:47,419 --> 00:29:51,131
half would land heads
and half tails, right?

357
00:29:51,173 --> 00:29:55,636
Looking close, I'd probably find
some heads grouped together.

358
00:29:55,677 --> 00:29:58,096
Does that mean anything?

359
00:29:58,138 --> 00:30:01,558
You see, no one knows
what causes leukaemia, Al.

360
00:30:01,642 --> 00:30:06,063
No one knows
what caused that cluster.

361
00:30:06,104 --> 00:30:10,317
I know what happened.
And I know who did it.

362
00:30:15,739 --> 00:30:17,783
Al, this is very important.

363
00:30:18,992 --> 00:30:22,120
I want you to tell me
who those people are.

364
00:30:22,204 --> 00:30:25,290
I'm not a rat.

365
00:30:25,332 --> 00:30:27,376
You know, it's important,

366
00:30:27,417 --> 00:30:30,295
because if there is something wrong,

367
00:30:30,379 --> 00:30:33,423
we need to disclose it
to the authorities.

368
00:30:33,507 --> 00:30:37,636
We need to get them out there
and have it cleaned up.

369
00:30:39,596 --> 00:30:42,724
You think about that and call me.

370
00:30:42,808 --> 00:30:44,726
Yeah. Yeah.

371
00:31:10,836 --> 00:31:13,005
Do you eat peanut butter?

372
00:31:14,506 --> 00:31:15,924
No.

373
00:31:16,008 --> 00:31:17,718
You've never eaten peanut butter?

374
00:31:17,801 --> 00:31:20,262
I guess everyone alive
has tried it,

375
00:31:20,345 --> 00:31:23,432
but I'm not a peanut butter fan.

376
00:31:25,100 --> 00:31:28,395
Did your son
ever eat peanut butter?

377
00:31:30,939 --> 00:31:34,610
- Do you eat bacon?
- Yes.

378
00:31:34,735 --> 00:31:38,113
- Yes.
- How often? How many slices?

379
00:31:41,491 --> 00:31:44,328
Do you have Teflon pans
in your kitchen?

380
00:31:44,411 --> 00:31:47,873
Do you chew sugarless gum?
Do you pump your own gas?

381
00:31:47,956 --> 00:31:51,543
Do you use hair spray?
Do you use artificial sweeteners?

382
00:31:51,668 --> 00:31:55,756
Smoke cigarettes? Drink diet soda?
Use tampons?

383
00:31:55,839 --> 00:31:57,758
Are your clothes ever dry-cleaned?

384
00:31:57,841 --> 00:32:01,136
Do you have silver fillings
in your teeth?

385
00:32:03,096 --> 00:32:08,143
You knew when you moved to Woburn
that its water didn't taste good?

386
00:32:08,268 --> 00:32:12,397
Yeah, but lots of places
the water doesn't taste so good.

387
00:32:12,481 --> 00:32:14,399
I agree with that.

388
00:32:14,483 --> 00:32:16,944
Did you ever consider
using bottled water?

389
00:32:17,027 --> 00:32:21,114
We used bottled water off and on,
split half and half.

390
00:32:21,198 --> 00:32:25,118
Like...we cooked with
regular water - tap water.

391
00:32:25,244 --> 00:32:28,288
We did other things,
like make orange juice.

392
00:32:28,372 --> 00:32:31,041
But to...drink just straight
water, we drank bottled water.

393
00:32:33,335 --> 00:32:37,881
Has a doctor ever said that you have
any immune system dysfunction?

394
00:32:37,965 --> 00:32:43,845
No. But when my son died,
they told us that was why he died.

395
00:32:43,929 --> 00:32:46,473
His immune system was...

396
00:32:47,558 --> 00:32:49,601
tore down to nothing.

397
00:32:55,232 --> 00:32:59,361
- Why did you have an autopsy?
- Because he was doing good.

398
00:32:59,403 --> 00:33:02,990
He only lived three months
with leukaemia

399
00:33:03,031 --> 00:33:05,033
and he looked fine.

400
00:33:05,117 --> 00:33:08,287
Did you talk to the doctor
about this?

401
00:33:08,370 --> 00:33:12,374
I had more like
a violent talk with him.

402
00:33:14,042 --> 00:33:18,046
- "Violent"? You were angry?
- Yelling at him.

403
00:33:18,088 --> 00:33:22,217
Your son seemed to be doing
all right. He was in remission?

404
00:33:22,301 --> 00:33:24,595
You were optimistic about his future

405
00:33:24,678 --> 00:33:27,598
and suddenly he became ill and died.

406
00:33:27,681 --> 00:33:30,225
And they said that was expected -

407
00:33:30,309 --> 00:33:34,855
that anybody with a disease like
leukaemia could die any minute.

408
00:33:36,607 --> 00:33:40,903
- But you were angry and upset.
- My son just died.

409
00:33:40,986 --> 00:33:45,699
I understand, I'm just
trying to recreate the event.

410
00:33:45,782 --> 00:33:49,703
You know when your child isn't well.

411
00:33:49,828 --> 00:33:52,289
You try to explain on the phone

412
00:33:52,372 --> 00:33:55,000
and they say,
"Has he got a temperature?"

413
00:33:55,083 --> 00:33:58,003
You say, "No."
"He's all right, then," they say.

414
00:33:58,086 --> 00:34:01,381
"Don't worry - bring him
into the clinic Monday."

415
00:34:03,175 --> 00:34:05,552
He died Monday morning.

416
00:34:07,554 --> 00:34:10,515
He was in the clinic when he died?

417
00:34:10,599 --> 00:34:12,184
No.

418
00:34:13,268 --> 00:34:17,189
He was in the car on the way.

419
00:34:26,823 --> 00:34:29,701
He died in the car
on the way to the clinic?

420
00:34:29,785 --> 00:34:34,831
He died on l-93,
up by the Somerville exit.

421
00:34:43,215 --> 00:34:47,427
My wife was yelling
that he'd stopped breathing.

422
00:34:47,469 --> 00:34:52,224
I pulled over
and tried to give him CPR.

423
00:34:54,268 --> 00:34:59,147
I was holding him in my lap.

424
00:35:01,942 --> 00:35:03,986
Lauren was...

425
00:35:05,070 --> 00:35:06,697
screaming.

426
00:35:09,074 --> 00:35:12,995
Cars and trucks rushing by.

427
00:35:16,331 --> 00:35:18,375
And...

428
00:35:19,459 --> 00:35:21,753
she helped...

429
00:35:25,215 --> 00:35:27,259
I'm sorry.

430
00:35:28,343 --> 00:35:30,387
It's all right.

431
00:35:33,515 --> 00:35:35,434
It's OK.

432
00:35:55,621 --> 00:35:57,706
These people can never testify.

433
00:35:57,789 --> 00:35:59,625
No.

434
00:36:34,868 --> 00:36:38,997
We'll have the first seven
monitor wells in this area,

435
00:36:39,081 --> 00:36:41,083
in the permeable rock here.

436
00:36:41,166 --> 00:36:42,876
All right. There's seven?

437
00:36:42,960 --> 00:36:44,962
Yes. I did say only seven.

438
00:36:45,045 --> 00:36:47,714
Now we'll probably
have 12, because...

439
00:36:47,798 --> 00:36:50,634
Hey! Hey!

440
00:36:53,554 --> 00:36:56,431
- Private property.
- Yes, your property.

441
00:36:56,515 --> 00:36:58,684
My property and you're trespassing.

442
00:36:58,767 --> 00:37:00,936
- Here.
- What the fuck is this?

443
00:37:01,019 --> 00:37:05,691
That's a court order, Mr Riley,
giving me the right to be here,

444
00:37:05,774 --> 00:37:09,194
and to inspect every inch
of your tannery, too.

445
00:37:09,319 --> 00:37:11,697
No, keep that. That's your copy.

446
00:37:14,700 --> 00:37:16,326
Let's go.

447
00:37:25,168 --> 00:37:28,964
I started working
when I was seven years old,

448
00:37:29,006 --> 00:37:32,759
sweeping the beam house floors
for my father,

449
00:37:32,843 --> 00:37:37,556
which he swept for his father
when he was seven years old.

450
00:37:38,640 --> 00:37:41,602
- Which my boys...
- I know. They swept it, too.

451
00:37:41,685 --> 00:37:46,565
Please answer the question I asked.
Silicone and trichlorethylene.

452
00:37:46,690 --> 00:37:48,525
These two chemicals mixed together

453
00:37:48,609 --> 00:37:51,778
are used to waterproof leather,
are they not?

454
00:37:53,322 --> 00:37:56,909
I asked you a question,
Mr Riley - again.

455
00:38:00,120 --> 00:38:03,874
Please inform your client that he's
obligated to answer my question.

456
00:38:15,427 --> 00:38:18,096
Let the record show
that the witness

457
00:38:18,180 --> 00:38:21,475
emptied a glass of water
on my conference table.

458
00:38:21,558 --> 00:38:27,189
What exactly do you intend to say
to me by pouring water on my table?

459
00:38:27,272 --> 00:38:30,943
It's how silicone
is used to waterproof leather.

460
00:38:31,068 --> 00:38:32,903
I'm answering your question.

461
00:38:32,986 --> 00:38:37,950
It's poured on,
like you poured water on my table.

462
00:38:38,075 --> 00:38:39,868
Yeah. Correct.

463
00:38:39,952 --> 00:38:42,996
So some of it must
spill off the leather,

464
00:38:43,080 --> 00:38:45,457
Iike the water spilling
off my table...

465
00:38:45,541 --> 00:38:47,918
and onto my rug.

466
00:38:48,669 --> 00:38:50,963
That's the part I'm interested in.

467
00:38:52,756 --> 00:38:55,968
The spilled silicone
and trichlorethylene, sir,

468
00:38:56,051 --> 00:38:58,095
how you disposed of that.

469
00:38:59,179 --> 00:39:03,809
- I never once used TCE.
- TCE? Did I say TCE?

470
00:39:03,892 --> 00:39:06,270
I didn't say TCE.

471
00:39:06,353 --> 00:39:08,647
I said trichlorethylene.

472
00:39:12,234 --> 00:39:14,152
You said TCE -

473
00:39:14,236 --> 00:39:17,447
as it is commonly known...

474
00:39:17,531 --> 00:39:20,158
to those who know it.

475
00:39:21,326 --> 00:39:24,997
Mr Riley, would you mind if
I checked your statements today

476
00:39:25,122 --> 00:39:28,667
against your records - invoices,
purchase orders and formulas?

477
00:39:28,750 --> 00:39:34,423
No. Be my guest.
They go back...three years.

478
00:39:34,506 --> 00:39:37,259
Everything before that, we dumped.

479
00:39:45,976 --> 00:39:50,105
- Jan, you're not listening.
- You've been out there three times.

480
00:39:50,188 --> 00:39:52,733
I know why
you find this unacceptable.

481
00:39:52,816 --> 00:39:56,486
But you don't know what it's like.
Riley is Woburn.

482
00:39:56,570 --> 00:39:59,489
His employees are loyal subjects.
They won't talk.

483
00:39:59,573 --> 00:40:02,701
Ex-employees, that's who
you should be talking to.

484
00:40:02,784 --> 00:40:07,581
- Disgruntled employees, they talk.
- You want me to go back there?

485
00:40:07,664 --> 00:40:12,794
This is THE case against Beatrice.
He's a liar. Go back and catch him.

486
00:40:12,920 --> 00:40:16,340
- You got the medical records?
- I can't...

487
00:40:16,381 --> 00:40:18,800
Just get it.

488
00:40:36,401 --> 00:40:40,072
This figure here,
this 100 an hour for Dr Cohen,

489
00:40:40,197 --> 00:40:42,824
that seems fair,
considering his pre-eminence.

490
00:40:42,908 --> 00:40:45,369
That's for his nights in the hotel.

