Oh, yes. What is that?
The Wildwood Conservancy.

735
01:01:54,805 --> 01:01:57,849
- Is that a conservation group?
- Yes, sir.

736
01:01:57,933 --> 01:02:02,479
I've donated the land as
a sanctuary for indigent wildlife.

737
01:02:04,815 --> 01:02:09,236
I don't think the indigent wildlife
has heard about this, Mr Riley.

738
01:02:09,319 --> 01:02:14,199
I've been there several times
and haven't seen any living thing.

739
01:02:14,283 --> 01:02:18,829
He says no, no, no.
He says yes once, I've got him.

740
01:02:18,912 --> 01:02:20,956
He's not that stupid.

741
01:02:21,039 --> 01:02:25,502
Keep him there long enough,
he'll figure a way to get you.

742
01:02:25,586 --> 01:02:27,379
I'm not that stupid.

743
01:02:32,175 --> 01:02:34,720
Mr Riley, experts
have testified in this court

744
01:02:34,845 --> 01:02:36,972
that your land, your 15 acres,

745
01:02:37,055 --> 01:02:40,434
is the most grotesquely polluted
land in New England.

746
01:02:40,517 --> 01:02:42,978
You have no idea how that happened?

747
01:02:43,061 --> 01:02:47,232
- No, sir.
- Does it upset you to learn this?

748
01:02:47,316 --> 01:02:51,069
- Very much so.
- Really? Why?

749
01:02:53,238 --> 01:02:55,699
And one last thing,

750
01:02:55,824 --> 01:02:58,744
unless you know exactly
what the answer is,

751
01:02:58,827 --> 01:03:02,331
never, ever ask a witness "why".

752
01:03:02,456 --> 01:03:04,082
Never.

753
01:03:07,920 --> 01:03:11,340
My factory is the oldest
surviving business in Woburn.

754
01:03:11,465 --> 01:03:14,843
When the other tanners moved out,
I stayed,

755
01:03:14,927 --> 01:03:18,305
even though that was
a very big financial burden.

756
01:03:18,388 --> 01:03:20,933
- That's not...
- Woburn is my home...

757
01:03:21,016 --> 01:03:22,643
That's not the question.

758
01:03:22,726 --> 01:03:27,356
He's trying to answer it,
Mr Schlichtmann. Let him.

759
01:03:36,198 --> 01:03:40,953
That land has been in my family
for three generations.

760
01:03:42,079 --> 01:03:44,998
That land to me is hallowed ground.

761
01:03:45,082 --> 01:03:49,878
So when you ask me would I be upset

762
01:03:50,003 --> 01:03:52,506
if someone desecrated it -

763
01:03:52,548 --> 01:03:56,552
Iand that's part of the town
that I love -

764
01:03:56,635 --> 01:04:00,055
my answer to your question,
Mr Schlichtmann...

765
01:04:03,517 --> 01:04:05,435
is yes.

766
01:04:22,661 --> 01:04:25,581
I have no further questions,
Your Honour.

767
01:04:29,543 --> 01:04:34,590
The sad part is, they rob themselves
of the blessing of giving.

768
01:04:34,673 --> 01:04:40,345
If somebody wrote a cheque
for the total budget of my church,

769
01:04:40,429 --> 01:04:44,266
it wouldn't affect my giving.

770
01:04:44,391 --> 01:04:48,228
Ain't nobody gonna rob me
of the blessing of giving!

771
01:04:48,312 --> 01:04:52,316
You know why folks ain't getting?
'Cause they ain't giving!

772
01:04:52,399 --> 01:04:57,196
Do not rob yourself
of the blessing of giving.

773
01:04:57,321 --> 01:05:01,825
You'll never guess what I did
last night. You'll like this.

774
01:05:01,909 --> 01:05:06,246
I pledged 200 to a televangelist. I'm
not kidding.

775
01:05:06,330 --> 01:05:09,458
He said,
"Give and ye shall receive."

776
01:05:09,541 --> 01:05:12,211
I know. I know what you're thinking.

777
01:05:12,294 --> 01:05:16,506
You're thinking, Gordon's losing it.
He's falling apart.

778
01:05:16,590 --> 01:05:19,676
He's probably
buying lottery tickets.

779
01:05:21,053 --> 01:05:23,680
I bought a few. I'll admit it.

780
01:05:23,764 --> 01:05:27,434
I know, but seriously,
the jackpot's 45 million.

781
01:05:27,559 --> 01:05:31,396
That's just this week!
You should see the lines out there.

782
01:05:34,358 --> 01:05:38,820
- Is that a gun?
- What?

783
01:05:41,990 --> 01:05:45,744
This? No. No, this is for you.

784
01:05:49,456 --> 01:05:52,292
My Krugerrands.
I've had them forever.

785
01:05:53,752 --> 01:05:56,004
I want you to have them.

786
01:05:56,088 --> 01:05:59,925
And this is the deed to my house.

787
01:06:00,050 --> 01:06:03,720
Here is Conway's
and Crowley's and Jan's.

788
01:06:03,845 --> 01:06:06,181
See, I've come bearing gifts.

789
01:06:11,436 --> 01:06:13,480
We really need the money.

790
01:06:19,486 --> 01:06:22,364
You can tell your child isn't well.

791
01:06:22,447 --> 01:06:27,077
"Has he got a temperature?" "No."
"He's all right, then", they say.

792
01:06:27,160 --> 01:06:33,333
"Bring him to the clinic Monday."
He died Monday morning.

793
01:06:33,417 --> 01:06:35,460
Start with Jimmy Anderson -

794
01:06:35,544 --> 01:06:39,131
countless trips to hospital,
futile chemotherapy treatments.

795
01:06:39,256 --> 01:06:44,595
Then the others, ending with Jared
Aufiero, dying on the highway.

796
01:06:44,720 --> 01:06:47,723
Could somebody get that?

797
01:06:51,560 --> 01:06:53,270
Where is everybody?

798
01:06:53,353 --> 01:06:58,233
You're just noticing now? Gordon
laid everybody off two weeks ago.

799
01:06:58,317 --> 01:07:02,321
Gordon, instead of sitting there
reading a magazine,

800
01:07:02,362 --> 01:07:05,908
why not go to Uncle Pete
and get me a staff?

801
01:07:06,033 --> 01:07:09,119
Good idea.
Why didn't I think of that?

802
01:07:13,415 --> 01:07:14,833
Hello?

803
01:07:27,137 --> 01:07:29,890
There was a Cheeseman
on the Mayflower.

804
01:07:29,973 --> 01:07:32,601
- This way, sir.
- Thank you.

805
01:07:32,684 --> 01:07:34,561
Jan, have a seat.

806
01:07:34,645 --> 01:07:37,814
You want something to drink?
Some coffee? Soda?

807
01:07:37,898 --> 01:07:40,359
You've been talking
without me present?

808
01:07:40,442 --> 01:07:44,488
No, we have been drinking coffee
without your being present.

809
01:07:44,571 --> 01:07:47,241
Don't be so paranoid.
They were early.

810
01:07:50,077 --> 01:07:53,580
- All right. What's up?
- Jerry?

811
01:07:53,664 --> 01:07:56,708
Last night, I was at a ball game.

812
01:07:56,792 --> 01:08:00,629
It was the seventh innings
and I was standing there,

813
01:08:00,754 --> 01:08:04,299
and it occurred to me
at that moment,

814
01:08:04,383 --> 01:08:08,136
unless you've proven that any...
What word should we use?

815
01:08:08,220 --> 01:08:10,138
- Chemicals?
- Poisons.

816
01:08:10,222 --> 01:08:13,267
If you like that word, I'll use it.

817
01:08:13,350 --> 01:08:18,689
Unless you've proven that poisons
reached the wells, there's no case.

818
01:08:18,772 --> 01:08:22,693
And therefore,
no need to make these families,

819
01:08:22,776 --> 01:08:24,653
who've already suffered so much,

820
01:08:24,736 --> 01:08:28,323
relive their suffering
all over again

821
01:08:28,448 --> 01:08:31,869
by putting them on the stand.

822
01:08:33,203 --> 01:08:36,331
- Your Honour, you've...
- That's interesting.

823
01:08:36,415 --> 01:08:39,585
- What?
- I'd have to agree with that.

824
01:08:39,668 --> 01:08:41,295
Your Honour, the...

825
01:08:41,378 --> 01:08:45,507
If the jury decides favourably
on the geological evidence,

826
01:08:45,591 --> 01:08:48,135
you could bring your families in.

827
01:08:48,260 --> 01:08:51,555
Your Honour, the jury
was expecting a human drama.

828
01:08:51,638 --> 01:08:54,850
For three months
they've had lessons in geology.

829
01:08:54,933 --> 01:08:58,312
We had to do that.
Now it's over - finally.

830
01:08:58,395 --> 01:09:02,482
Now we have to see where we are
before moving on,

831
01:09:02,566 --> 01:09:05,903
and subjecting these families
to more trauma than necessary,

832
01:09:05,986 --> 01:09:08,113
because that would just be cruel.

833
01:09:08,197 --> 01:09:11,783
- They want to testify.
- The decision is made.

834
01:09:11,909 --> 01:09:14,870
- It's the defendant's plan.
- It's my plan.

835
01:09:14,953 --> 01:09:17,331
Right from the beginning,
he threatened...

836
01:09:17,456 --> 01:09:19,708
It's MY plan!

837
01:09:27,966 --> 01:09:29,551
Now...

838
01:09:30,427 --> 01:09:36,433
my plan is to present the jury
with some simple questions.

839
01:09:37,809 --> 01:09:40,521
How you answer
these three questions,

840
01:09:40,604 --> 01:09:43,357
will determine whether
this trial continues.

841
01:09:44,858 --> 01:09:47,528
I don't disagree -
I don't understand them.

842
01:09:47,611 --> 01:09:50,280
What don't you understand?
They're straightforward questions.

843
01:09:50,364 --> 01:09:54,034
Have the plaintiffs established,
by preponderance of evidence,

844
01:09:54,117 --> 01:09:59,248
that chemicals containing TCE
were disposed of on these lands

845
01:09:59,331 --> 01:10:06,171
after October 1, 1964
and August 27, 1968, respectively,

846
01:10:06,255 --> 01:10:09,591
and did those chemicals contribute
to the well water contamination?

847
01:10:09,675 --> 01:10:14,304
What were these dates?
Where are they from? Out of a hat?

848
01:10:14,388 --> 01:10:16,139
Question two.

849
01:10:16,223 --> 01:10:19,726
What, according to
a preponderance of the evidence,

850
01:10:19,810 --> 01:10:23,272
was the earliest time
at which these chemicals

851
01:10:23,355 --> 01:10:26,775
substantially contributed
to the wells' contamination?

852
01:10:26,859 --> 01:10:28,485
How can they determine that?

853
01:10:28,569 --> 01:10:32,239
Science can't even determine
when the chemicals arrived

854
01:10:32,322 --> 01:10:35,576
with the precision
that you're asking of the jurors.

855
01:10:35,659 --> 01:10:37,452
And finally, three.

856
01:10:37,536 --> 01:10:40,163
What, according to
a preponderance of the evidence,

857
01:10:40,247 --> 01:10:43,250
was the earliest time -
again, month and year -

858
01:10:43,333 --> 01:10:46,378
at which substantial contribution
referred to in question two

859
01:10:46,461 --> 01:10:48,755
was caused, if it was,

860
01:10:48,839 --> 01:10:52,342
by the negligent conduct
of the defendants?

861
01:10:52,426 --> 01:10:55,721
It's like English translated into
Japanese back into English again.

862
01:10:55,804 --> 01:10:57,264
I've heard enough.

863
01:10:57,347 --> 01:11:00,434
Your Honour,
no one can answer these.

864
01:11:00,517 --> 01:11:02,978
You're asking for answers
that are unknowable.

865
01:11:03,061 --> 01:11:04,521
I've heard enough.

866
01:11:04,605 --> 01:11:08,358
You're asking for a fiction
that stands for truth, but isn't.

867
01:11:08,442 --> 01:11:09,443
Enough!

868
01:11:10,736 --> 01:11:16,700
Once again, I remind you not
to discuss your views outside,

869
01:11:16,783 --> 01:11:19,161
and excuse you...

870
01:11:21,872 --> 01:11:24,958
Don't worry about it.
Everything's under control.

871
01:11:25,918 --> 01:11:31,673
And excuse you
to your deliberations. Thank you.

872
01:12:56,425 --> 01:12:58,677
I've never done this.

873
01:12:58,719 --> 01:13:00,721
In 45 years of practising,

874
01:13:00,804 --> 01:13:04,266
I've never
waited in a corridor for a jury.

875
01:13:04,349 --> 01:13:07,311
- I always do.
- I can tell.

876
01:13:07,394 --> 01:13:10,189
You're good at it.

877
01:13:10,230 --> 01:13:12,608
You seem so at peace doing it.

878
01:13:17,446 --> 01:13:21,533
What do you think?
ls it good they're out this long?

879
01:13:21,617 --> 01:13:24,786
- For who?
- For me, of course.

880
01:13:27,080 --> 01:13:30,375
You can never tell.
It could mean anything.

881
01:13:30,459 --> 01:13:34,838
It could mean jury duty's more fun
than working at the post office.

882
01:13:36,757 --> 01:13:40,969
- It's bad for both of you.
- You think?

883
01:13:42,554 --> 01:13:44,598
Well, here's my take.

884
01:13:46,016 --> 01:13:48,143
Guilty.

885
01:13:49,311 --> 01:13:53,148
Not guilty.
That's what they're going to say.

886
01:13:53,273 --> 01:13:56,652
Nothing to do with dates
or ground-water measurements

887
01:13:56,735 --> 01:14:01,198
or any of that crap,
which nobody understands anyway.

888
01:14:01,281 --> 01:14:05,035
It's going to come down to people,
like always.

889
01:14:05,118 --> 01:14:08,872
You found someone
who saw him dumping stuff.

890
01:14:08,997 --> 01:14:12,751
You didn't find anyone who saw me.

891
01:14:15,712 --> 01:14:18,882
- What's your take?
- They'll see the truth.

892
01:14:18,966 --> 01:14:20,717
The truth?

893
01:14:22,010 --> 01:14:25,305
We're talking about a court of law.

894
01:14:25,389 --> 01:14:28,600
You've been around
long enough to know

895
01:14:28,684 --> 01:14:31,770
courtrooms aren't
where you look for the truth.

896
01:14:31,854 --> 01:14:35,983
You're lucky to find anything
that even resembles the truth.

897
01:14:38,944 --> 01:14:43,198
You disagree. Well, since when?

898
01:14:44,366 --> 01:14:46,368
Eight kids are dead, Jerry.

899
01:14:48,579 --> 01:14:53,083
Jan, that suit fits you better
than the sentimentality.

900
01:14:53,166 --> 01:14:56,920
That's not how you
made all that money, is it?

901
01:14:57,004 --> 01:15:02,050
It wasn't about dead children from
the minute you filed the complaint.

902
01:15:02,134 --> 01:15:06,972
The minute it entered
the justice system. Oh, yes.

903
01:15:11,351 --> 01:15:13,645
I know you like to gamble.

904
01:15:13,770 --> 01:15:16,231
High-stakes gambler,
that's your profession.

905
01:15:16,315 --> 01:15:20,360
Why not test your faith
in the righteousness of our courts

906
01:15:20,444 --> 01:15:22,988
with a high-stakes gamble?

907
01:15:27,242 --> 01:15:30,746
If that's a settlement offer,
Jerry, it's not enough.

908
01:15:30,829 --> 01:15:34,249
- That's not what I hear.
- Who said that?

909
01:15:34,374 --> 01:15:39,171
The IRS, telling us they have
a lien on any eventual settlement

910
01:15:39,296 --> 01:15:43,467
in order to recover
over 2.5 million in unpaid taxes.

911
01:15:46,595 --> 01:15:48,555
But all right...

912
01:15:48,639 --> 01:15:54,061
What if I would add
six zeros onto that?

913
01:15:54,144 --> 01:15:59,107
That would be - what? - 20 million.

914
01:16:00,275 --> 01:16:03,320
Now, that would put things
in perspective, wouldn't it?

915
01:16:03,403 --> 01:16:06,907
As far as truth, justice
and dead children go?

916
01:16:06,990 --> 01:16:09,826
If you want to talk
about a settlement,

917
01:16:09,910 --> 01:16:13,080
get the decision-makers together
and talk seriously.

918
01:16:13,163 --> 01:16:15,791
The decision-makers are here,
aren't they?

919
01:16:15,874 --> 01:16:17,793
You're looking at Mr Beatrice.

920
01:16:17,876 --> 01:16:21,338
I don't have to call anybody. Do you?

921
01:16:24,883 --> 01:16:27,886
It's just you and me.

922
01:16:27,928 --> 01:16:31,765
We're like kings. We are kings.

923
01:16:32,850 --> 01:16:35,519
Sitting in our castle,
deciding important things.

924
01:16:35,602 --> 01:16:38,146
Deciding the fates of others.

925
01:16:38,272 --> 01:16:41,400
And counting money.
In our counting room!

926
01:16:56,915 --> 01:17:00,294
Tell you what. I'll leave this here,

927
01:17:00,377 --> 01:17:03,755
go back down the hall
to my throne room

928
01:17:03,839 --> 01:17:06,508
and await your decision.

929
01:17:12,639 --> 01:17:15,100
If you really want the truth, Jan,

930
01:17:15,184 --> 01:17:21,106
Iook for it where it is -
at the bottom of a bottomless pit.

931
01:18:28,090 --> 01:18:32,010
Mr Foreman, members of the jury, have
you reached a verdict?

932
01:18:32,094 --> 01:18:33,929
Yes, Your Honour.

933
01:18:47,734 --> 01:18:53,073
With respect to W.R. Grace,
the jury has answered...

934
01:18:53,156 --> 01:18:57,744
"yes" to question one regarding
trichlorethylene contamination,

935
01:18:57,828 --> 01:19:00,372
requiring the case against Grace

936
01:19:00,414 --> 01:19:03,083
to go to a second stage
of this trial.

937
01:19:04,334 --> 01:19:11,508
In regard to Beatrice, the jury
has answered "no" to question one

938
01:19:11,592 --> 01:19:14,970
in all its points
pertaining to contamination

939
01:19:15,053 --> 01:19:19,057
which renders questions two
and three inapplicable,

940
01:19:19,141 --> 01:19:21,101
ending the case against Beatrice.

941
01:19:21,185 --> 01:19:25,314
- Mr Facher, you're excused.
- Thank you, Your Honour.

942
01:19:26,815 --> 01:19:33,614
We are going to take
a break now, until after lunch.

943
01:19:33,697 --> 01:19:37,451
Once again, I remind you
not to talk to anyone

944
01:19:37,576 --> 01:19:39,703
about your deliberations here...

945
01:19:52,216 --> 01:19:56,970
Disappointed?
Not at all. This is a victory.

946
01:19:57,054 --> 01:20:01,725
This sends a message that companies
can no longer get away with this.

947
01:20:01,808 --> 01:20:04,353
- So what now?
- Right now?

948
01:20:04,478 --> 01:20:08,065
I think we should celebrate.
What do you think? Yes?

949
01:20:08,148 --> 01:20:13,278
You'll proceed against Grace,
no matter how long it takes?

950
01:20:14,821 --> 01:20:18,742
We have to
get out of this case fast.

951
01:20:18,867 --> 01:20:20,911
That's our only strategy left.

952
01:20:22,412 --> 01:20:25,666
The good news is
Grace wants to talk.

953
01:20:25,749 --> 01:20:30,087
They want us to see their executive
vice-president, AI Eustis.

954
01:20:30,170 --> 01:20:33,799
So we need to know
what our squeal point is.

955
01:20:34,883 --> 01:20:39,179
8 million. 8 million
will just about get us out of hock.

956
01:20:40,806 --> 01:20:43,684
Gordon knows the numbers.

957
01:20:50,899 --> 01:20:55,028
Jan, every dollar we spend
is a dollar we don't have.

958
01:20:55,112 --> 01:20:58,115
We are floating on credit
without a net.

959
01:20:58,198 --> 01:21:02,244
I don't need a net.
Mortgage my house. I don't care.

960
01:21:03,036 --> 01:21:08,417
I have.
And Kevin's and Bill's and mine.

961
01:21:08,500 --> 01:21:13,881
I've cashed in our retirement plans
and life-insurance. And it's gone.

962
01:21:13,964 --> 01:21:16,592
Let me put it this way,

963
01:21:16,675 --> 01:21:22,848
if we can't appear we've got money
they won't give us 8 million.

964
01:21:22,931 --> 01:21:26,768
They won't give us eight cents.
You know that.

965
01:21:26,894 --> 01:21:28,937
You all know that.

966
01:21:37,613 --> 01:21:39,656
It's our nicest suite.

967
01:21:39,740 --> 01:21:45,204
Living room, dining room,
two bedrooms, a den, a lovely view.

968
01:21:45,287 --> 01:21:47,331
It's 2,400 a night.

969
01:21:49,541 --> 01:21:51,376
For our inner strength.

970
01:21:52,377 --> 01:21:55,422
- On the card.
- Why not?

971
01:21:58,175 --> 01:22:00,385
Farmers' Bank of lowa.

972
01:22:22,824 --> 01:22:24,243
Hey, there!

973
01:22:24,326 --> 01:22:26,578
- Jan Schlichtmann.
- AI Eustis.

974
01:22:26,662 --> 01:22:29,790
How are you?
Sorry I'm late. I got lost.

975
01:22:29,873 --> 01:22:32,000
- Got lost?
- Yes.

976
01:22:32,084 --> 01:22:33,961
How did you manage that?

977
01:22:34,044 --> 01:22:36,129
I've never been here before so...

978
01:22:36,213 --> 01:22:39,091
What kind of Harvard man are you?

979
01:22:40,217 --> 01:22:42,344
The Cornell kind.

980
01:22:42,427 --> 01:22:48,100
Cornell?
I thought you went to Harvard?

981
01:22:48,183 --> 01:22:53,647
I'm sure somebody said that
you went to Harvard! Cornell!

982
01:22:53,730 --> 01:22:55,691
Yes.

983
01:22:55,774 --> 01:22:58,861
Well, listen, Cornell is...
is a damn good school.

984
01:22:59,444 --> 01:23:02,322
Damn good.

985
01:23:02,364 --> 01:23:04,408
So what do you want?

986
01:23:05,492 --> 01:23:09,162
Well, I could take you
through it step by step

987
01:23:09,288 --> 01:23:13,417
or you could take
this with you and study it.

988
01:23:13,500 --> 01:23:15,419
It's a little complicated but...

989
01:23:15,502 --> 01:23:18,714
It's an unspoken rule
of the Harvard Club -

990
01:23:18,797 --> 01:23:22,092
business is never transacted here.

991
01:23:22,134 --> 01:23:25,387
I meant, what do you want to drink?

992
01:23:26,930 --> 01:23:31,351
I wanted to reach across
and strangle him with his tie.

993
01:23:31,435 --> 01:23:33,729
Instead, I sat there for two hours

994
01:23:33,854 --> 01:23:38,025
and listened to him
talk about selling his yacht.

995
01:23:38,108 --> 01:23:43,906
You know, sometimes
I actually prefer the 35-footer.

996
01:23:43,989 --> 01:23:46,325
Because I can crew it myself,

997
01:23:46,408 --> 01:23:51,079
I can be all by myself out there
alone. It's magnificent.

998
01:23:51,163 --> 01:23:54,833
And there's no... Nobody can
call you. Nobody can beep you.

999
01:23:54,958 --> 01:23:57,044
Nobody can fax you.

1000
01:23:57,127 --> 01:23:59,338
There's no lawsuits.

1001
01:23:59,463 --> 01:24:02,507
You know what I'm talking about.
You sail?

1002
01:24:02,591 --> 01:24:05,636
- No.
- You don't sail?

1003
01:24:07,012 --> 01:24:11,225
- Finally, we went to his office.
- Let's sit down.

1004
01:24:11,308 --> 01:24:15,145
Come on. It's more comfortable.
Have a seat.

1005
01:24:15,270 --> 01:24:18,565
He comes around the desk,
he sits down.

1006
01:24:20,734 --> 01:24:22,236
Go ahead, sit down.

1007
01:24:22,319 --> 01:24:25,989
He puts his feet up
on this French antique thing

1008
01:24:26,823 --> 01:24:30,202
and he tells me to put my feet up.

1009
01:24:30,285 --> 01:24:32,746
Put your feet up. Come on.

1010
01:24:32,829 --> 01:24:35,916
- No, thank you.
- No, go ahead.

1011
01:24:35,999 --> 01:24:38,961
- Go ahead.
- No, really, I'm fine.

1012
01:24:39,044 --> 01:24:42,256
Nothing's going to break.
Put them up.

1013
01:24:42,339 --> 01:24:46,552
It was weird - all this talk about
putting my feet on this table.

1014
01:24:46,635 --> 01:24:49,680
It's all right - I mean it.
Try it. Come on.

1015
01:24:49,763 --> 01:24:51,598
Put your feet up.

1016
01:25:00,524 --> 01:25:07,030
There. Now, I can afford to pay you
almost anything you ask.

1017
01:25:07,114 --> 01:25:09,658
It's not the money.

1018
01:25:09,741 --> 01:25:12,661
But a settlement that high
says we're guilty.

1019
01:25:12,744 --> 01:25:16,915
That says to every two-bit
personal injury lawyer in Boston,

1020
01:25:16,999 --> 01:25:19,209
Iet's sign up everyone in Woburn.

1021
01:25:19,293 --> 01:25:22,796
Creates a shark effect,
and that I can't afford.

1022
01:25:22,880 --> 01:25:24,840
Give me a number.

1023
01:25:26,300 --> 01:25:28,594
I'm not negotiating with myself, Al,

1024
01:25:28,719 --> 01:25:32,097
throwing out numbers
you can say no to.

1025
01:25:32,181 --> 01:25:34,725
- You give me one.
- 8 million.

1026
01:25:37,811 --> 01:25:41,648
He said 8 million?

1027
01:25:41,732 --> 01:25:43,192
8 million.

1028
01:25:45,068 --> 01:25:47,738
I can't go to the families
with that.

1029
01:25:47,821 --> 01:25:50,115
Wait! What? Who? What families?

1030
01:25:50,199 --> 01:25:52,951
I can't go to them empty-handed.

1031
01:25:53,035 --> 01:25:54,995
What are you talking about?

1032
01:25:55,078 --> 01:25:59,750
Since when is that empty-handed?
8 million is a lot of money!

1033
01:26:01,376 --> 01:26:03,420
I owe them more than that.

1034
01:26:03,503 --> 01:26:06,048
What do you owe them?

1035
01:26:06,173 --> 01:26:08,383
Do you owe them your career?

1036
01:26:08,467 --> 01:26:10,594
You're talking
about our careers here!

1037
01:26:10,677 --> 01:26:13,931
- You owe them that?
- And OUR families!

1038
01:26:14,014 --> 01:26:15,891
That's what we're talking here.

1039
01:26:15,974 --> 01:26:18,435
Our families...

1040
01:26:18,477 --> 01:26:20,896
Don't do it.

1041
01:26:23,524 --> 01:26:26,068
Don't go for broke on this one.

1042
01:26:26,151 --> 01:26:28,779
It isn't worth it, Jan.

1043
01:26:53,679 --> 01:26:57,850
Nobody calls any more?
Not even the creditors.

1044
01:26:59,351 --> 01:27:01,186
Are the phones still working?

1045
01:27:10,612 --> 01:27:12,656
Schlichtmann, Conway and Crowley.

1046
01:27:15,492 --> 01:27:17,327
Just a moment, please.

1047
01:27:18,287 --> 01:27:19,872
Someone named Grendan.

1048
01:27:19,955 --> 01:27:21,623
Creditor.

1049
01:27:21,707 --> 01:27:26,378
- Are you here?
- Do I look like I'm here?

1050
01:27:28,005 --> 01:27:30,299
He's in a meeting at the moment.

1051
01:27:30,424 --> 01:27:33,510
Do me a favour, Gordon? Shut up.

1052
01:27:35,470 --> 01:27:36,930
What?

1053
01:27:37,014 --> 01:27:40,559
I'm tired of hearing you
moan about money.

1054
01:27:40,642 --> 01:27:42,769
This isn't about money any more.

1055
01:27:42,895 --> 01:27:46,648
No? What's it about?

1056
01:27:48,483 --> 01:27:49,943
What's it about, Jan?

1057
01:27:50,027 --> 01:27:53,780
- Look, let's all...
- No, I want to know.

1058
01:27:53,906 --> 01:27:59,870
I want to know what I gave up
my house for - my credit, my life!

1059
01:27:59,953 --> 01:28:02,080
Would you take 10 million?

1060
01:28:02,164 --> 01:28:04,291
- Yes.
- But not eight?

1061
01:28:04,374 --> 01:28:05,375
No.

1062
01:28:05,500 --> 01:28:09,338
So 10 million
is some mythic struggle,

1063
01:28:09,463 --> 01:28:11,757
but eight is just another lawsuit!

1064
01:28:11,840 --> 01:28:15,427
If they're willing to pay eight
then it's not enough.

1065
01:28:15,552 --> 01:28:18,847
- That makes sense!
- It makes perfect sense.

1066
01:28:18,931 --> 01:28:22,351
So you'll only accept
what they won't give us?

1067
01:28:22,434 --> 01:28:24,061
Listen to yourself!

1068
01:28:24,144 --> 01:28:29,358
I'm sick of listening to you.
I've lost enough because of you.

1069
01:28:29,483 --> 01:28:34,238
You'd have nothing but for me.
All you have, I got for you!

1070
01:28:34,321 --> 01:28:38,158
I don't have anything!
What do I have?

1071
01:28:38,283 --> 01:28:42,412
I got a couple of bucks
and some bus transfers.

1072
01:28:42,496 --> 01:28:47,209
I've got a savings account
from when I was 12.

1073
01:28:47,292 --> 01:28:49,753
Here - there's 37 in here.

1074
01:28:49,836 --> 01:28:52,506
With interest after 25 years,
probably 47!

1075
01:28:52,589 --> 01:28:55,342
Take it! Add it to the war chest.

1076
01:28:55,425 --> 01:28:57,469
Use it to fight injustice!

1077
01:28:57,553 --> 01:29:01,849
Go down in flames with it
for all I care.

1078
01:29:01,932 --> 01:29:04,935
Only next time...
Next time - that's a laugh!

1079
01:29:05,018 --> 01:29:09,106
Ask us if we want
to go down with you!

1080
01:30:18,759 --> 01:30:21,845
I'd like to leave a message
for AI Eustis, please.

1081
01:30:28,852 --> 01:30:33,148
I've been informed that a settlement
agreement has been reached.

1082
01:30:33,232 --> 01:30:35,234
As a condition of this agreement,

1083
01:30:35,317 --> 01:30:39,238
the exact terms shall remain
private among the parties involved.

1084
01:30:40,405 --> 01:30:42,783
Thank you for your service...

1085
01:30:42,908 --> 01:30:46,828
Our contingency fee,
as you know, as you agreed to -

1086
01:30:55,921 --> 01:30:58,298
or 2.2 million.

1087
01:30:58,423 --> 01:31:02,928
Our expenses - what we actually
paid out trying this case -

1088
01:31:03,011 --> 01:31:04,930
comes to 3.5 million.

1089
01:31:11,854 --> 01:31:17,776
and dividing it equally,
comes out to 375,000 per family.

1090
01:31:27,953 --> 01:31:29,997
And they're
gonna clean the place up?

1091
01:31:31,540 --> 01:31:33,166
No.

1092
01:31:36,795 --> 01:31:39,339
When you first came out here,
Mr Schlichtmann,

1093
01:31:39,423 --> 01:31:46,013
when we first spoke, I told you
I wasn't interested in money.

1094
01:31:46,096 --> 01:31:47,931
Here it comes.

1095
01:31:48,015 --> 01:31:51,226
What I wanted
was an apology from someone

1096
01:31:51,310 --> 01:31:54,021
for what they did to my son.

1097
01:31:55,147 --> 01:31:57,983
And you said, money is the apology.

1098
01:31:58,066 --> 01:32:02,154
That's how they apologise -
with their chequebooks.

1099
01:32:05,115 --> 01:32:07,659
Would you call this an apology?

1100
01:32:09,494 --> 01:32:10,954
No.

1101
01:32:11,038 --> 01:32:15,334
The only meaningful apology
you're going to get is from me.

1102
01:32:15,417 --> 01:32:17,169
I'm sorry.

1103
01:32:20,964 --> 01:32:23,634
I'm afraid that isn't meaningful.

1104
01:32:25,302 --> 01:32:29,515
Mrs Anderson, you're looking
at four guys who are broke.

1105
01:32:29,598 --> 01:32:31,517
We lost everything trying this case.

1106
01:32:33,519 --> 01:32:37,648
How can you even begin
to compare what you've lost

1107
01:32:37,731 --> 01:32:39,775
to what we've lost?

1108
01:33:24,361 --> 01:33:28,866
Listen, the minute you put money
on the table, things turn ugly.

1109
01:33:28,949 --> 01:33:31,410
It happens every time. Forget it.

1110
01:33:31,493 --> 01:33:33,745
But she's right.

1111
01:33:34,913 --> 01:33:36,957
She's not right.

1112
01:33:39,126 --> 01:33:43,881
It's cold. It's wet. We're
in the swamp. I want to go home.

1113
01:33:43,964 --> 01:33:46,717
Someone out here saw what happened.

1114
01:33:46,800 --> 01:33:50,345
You can't do what Riley did
without somebody seeing it.

1115
01:33:51,930 --> 01:33:54,183
You're talking about the case.

1116
01:33:54,266 --> 01:33:56,226
The case is over.

1117
01:34:06,945 --> 01:34:09,781
Yeah, I know. They want out, right?

1118
01:34:09,865 --> 01:34:12,618
It's time they went
their separate way.

1119
01:34:12,701 --> 01:34:15,037
You know what I think of that?

1120
01:34:15,120 --> 01:34:17,915
Fine. Let 'em.

1121
01:34:17,956 --> 01:34:22,085
- I can imagine worse things.
- Like what?

1122
01:34:22,169 --> 01:34:24,922
So what if we have to start over?

1123
01:34:25,005 --> 01:34:29,885
We did it once.
We can do it again, the two of us.

1124
01:34:38,352 --> 01:34:44,566
Oh, I see. When you say it's over,
you mean it's over.

1125
01:34:46,235 --> 01:34:49,321
It's time for me
to go my separate way.

1126
01:34:52,908 --> 01:34:55,577
You always went
your separate way, Jan.

1127
01:35:58,557 --> 01:36:00,184
Thank you.

1128
01:36:58,450 --> 01:37:03,455
This is how silicone is
put on leather to waterproof it.

1129
01:37:03,539 --> 01:37:06,917
Like you poured water on my table.

1130
01:37:07,000 --> 01:37:09,044
Yeah.

1131
01:37:16,927 --> 01:37:20,597
So some of it must
spill off the leather,

1132
01:37:20,681 --> 01:37:23,642
Iike the water
spilling off my table.

1133
01:37:27,604 --> 01:37:30,148
That's the part I'm interested in.

1134
01:37:30,274 --> 01:37:33,277
The spilled silicone
and trichlorethylene, sir -

1135
01:37:33,360 --> 01:37:35,404
how you disposed of that.

1136
01:37:46,999 --> 01:37:50,002
We're just here
to look at your records.

1137
01:38:06,393 --> 01:38:09,146
I didn't call him, he just came.

1138
01:38:09,229 --> 01:38:14,276
- You just let him in?
- Of course I did.

1139
01:38:36,131 --> 01:38:39,718
You know how sometimes
you get so close to something

1140
01:38:39,843 --> 01:38:41,887
that you lose sight of it?

1141
01:38:45,682 --> 01:38:48,560
I kept looking for someone

1142
01:38:48,644 --> 01:38:52,064
who saw Riley dumping
barrels of poison, when l...

1143
01:38:52,147 --> 01:38:56,610
I should've been looking for someone
who helped him clean it up.

1144
01:39:04,076 --> 01:39:09,414
Why did you rent two dump trucks
and a front loader in October '81?

1145
01:39:09,498 --> 01:39:13,418
Or is this just
part of your job at the tannery?

1146
01:39:15,212 --> 01:39:19,258
- Mr Granger?
- I don't have to talk to you.

1147
01:39:19,341 --> 01:39:24,012
I can tell you to leave
and I'd be within my rights.

1148
01:39:24,096 --> 01:39:26,473
Yes, you would.

1149
01:39:38,735 --> 01:39:43,699
In the fall of 1981, Mr Riley
instructed me to rent a loader

1150
01:39:43,824 --> 01:39:47,244
and two 10-wheel dump trucks.

1151
01:39:47,327 --> 01:39:51,164
- Did he tell you why?
- Yes, he did.

1152
01:39:51,290 --> 01:39:55,627
Everything goes. I don't want
to see anything but topsoil.

1153
01:39:55,711 --> 01:40:01,216
Didn't it seem strange
that he had to get rid of it now?

1154
01:40:01,300 --> 01:40:04,678
I don't want to know where.
Just take it.

1155
01:40:04,761 --> 01:40:07,431
He told me city inspectors
were coming.

1156
01:40:07,514 --> 01:40:09,975
He didn't want them to see it.

1157
01:40:15,272 --> 01:40:17,733
This went on for several nights.

1158
01:40:17,816 --> 01:40:19,860
Fill the trucks, trucks drive off,

1159
01:40:19,943 --> 01:40:24,031
trucks come back empty,
we fill them up again.

1160
01:40:25,741 --> 01:40:27,784
On the last night...

1161
01:40:27,868 --> 01:40:30,078
On the last night, what?

1162
01:40:31,788 --> 01:40:34,833
Are you sure you didn't
see some kids there?

1163
01:40:34,917 --> 01:40:38,670
- Lighting fires, drinking beers?
- I've nothing to say.

1164
01:40:38,754 --> 01:40:42,090
It'd be hard to forget.
You know, it's a...

1165
01:40:42,174 --> 01:40:44,218
Apparently, it was quite a sight.

1166
01:40:47,971 --> 01:40:49,223
Go, go, go.

1167
01:40:49,348 --> 01:40:51,892
Watch out!

1168
01:40:52,017 --> 01:40:55,020
This is private property!
You little punks!

1169
01:40:55,103 --> 01:40:56,563
That's you!

1170
01:40:56,647 --> 01:41:01,151
You know, mister, I'm sorry.
Here's something to make up for it.

1171
01:41:01,235 --> 01:41:03,362
There you go! There - fry!

1172
01:41:05,030 --> 01:41:07,032
I'll have you arrested!

1173
01:41:07,115 --> 01:41:11,411
It's like that now!
You want some of that? Eat it!

1174
01:41:28,262 --> 01:41:31,098
Let's go! Let's go!

1175
01:41:32,933 --> 01:41:35,894
- Get the fuck out!
- Come on.

1176
01:41:46,154 --> 01:41:48,699
Did Riley threaten you at all

1177
01:41:48,824 --> 01:41:52,953
with what might happen to you
if you ever came forward?

1178
01:41:53,036 --> 01:41:54,621
No, sir.

1179
01:41:54,705 --> 01:41:58,458
He didn't say anything
at all in this regard?

1180
01:42:02,963 --> 01:42:06,049
He gave me
a couple of Celtics tickets.

1181
01:42:06,133 --> 01:42:08,802
Told me to keep my mouth shut.

1182
01:42:45,714 --> 01:42:48,550
The appeals process
is even more Byzantine

1183
01:42:48,634 --> 01:42:50,636
than the trial it's appealing.

1184
01:42:52,804 --> 01:42:55,140
It takes longer, it costs more,

1185
01:42:55,224 --> 01:42:57,893
its outcome is even less promising.

1186
01:42:59,102 --> 01:43:02,940
Only five cases in 50
will win in appeals court,

1187
01:43:03,023 --> 01:43:06,777
odds as easy to calculate
as they are discouraging.

1188
01:43:06,860 --> 01:43:09,154
They're 10 to 1 against.

1189
01:43:09,279 --> 01:43:12,115
Just about any bet at any table

1190
01:43:12,199 --> 01:43:14,993
in any casino
anywhere in the world...

1191
01:43:15,077 --> 01:43:16,912
is better than that.

1192
01:43:20,123 --> 01:43:24,253
I have the evidence but not the
resources or the gambling spirit

1193
01:43:24,336 --> 01:43:27,714
to appeal the decision in this case.

1194
01:43:29,049 --> 01:43:31,260
I have no money, no partners,

1195
01:43:31,385 --> 01:43:34,388
and, it seems, no clients any more.

1196
01:43:36,306 --> 01:43:40,519
The Woburn case has become what it
was when it first came to me -

1197
01:43:40,561 --> 01:43:42,396
an orphan.

1198
01:43:42,479 --> 01:43:45,816
I'm forwarding it on to you,

1199
01:43:45,858 --> 01:43:50,404
knowing you may not want it
any more than I did at first.

1200
01:43:51,530 --> 01:43:54,449
If you do decide to take it on,

1201
01:43:54,533 --> 01:43:58,287
I hope you'll be able to succeed
where I've failed.

1202
01:43:58,412 --> 01:44:02,249
If you calculate success
and failure as I always have,

1203
01:44:02,332 --> 01:44:05,711
in money divided neatly
into human suffering,

1204
01:44:05,752 --> 01:44:08,380
the arithmetic says...

1205
01:44:08,463 --> 01:44:10,507
I failed completely.

1206
01:44:12,092 --> 01:44:15,929
What it doesn't say
is if I could go back,

1207
01:44:16,054 --> 01:44:21,768
knowing what I know now and where
I'd end up if I got involved,

1208
01:44:21,852 --> 01:44:24,813
knowing all the numbers,
all the odds,

1209
01:44:24,897 --> 01:44:26,940
all the angles...

1210
01:44:32,487 --> 01:44:34,740
I'd do it again.

1211
01:45:24,039 --> 01:45:25,707
Sorry.

1212
01:46:26,894 --> 01:46:28,520
Jesus!

1213
01:47:31,792 --> 01:47:33,377
I'm sorry. Yes?

1214
01:47:33,460 --> 01:47:37,548
The purpose of these questions
is not to humiliate you,

1215
01:47:37,631 --> 01:47:40,717
but to verify
the assets that you've declared.

1216
01:47:40,801 --> 01:47:42,344
I understand.

